## Explanation:

### Solution 01

- We have to find all the permutations of words present in a fix size string,
- The possible size is the ***(length of any word * size of words).***
- If the given string has a size less than ***(length of any word * size of words),*** simply return ans.
- If not then put given words into an unordered map `unordered_map<string, int> mp`
- Now in the next loop, we’ll iterate elements from start till ***n-(len*size)*** & take another map to keep the word track of the current substring.
- In the next loop, we took the string that can be the ans. we’re keeping the words in current & check if this is present in the given words, if not then break the loop.
- Else we keep track of this in another map, if any point current element value in the present map became greater than the given words map then break the loop.
- Finally, if both map matches then push the index to ans vector.
- **Time complexity:** O(n^2).

---

## Code:

```cpp
//Solution 01:
****class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findSubstring(string s, vector<string>& words) {
        int len = words[0].length(), size = words.size(), n = s.size();
        vector<int> ans;
        unordered_map<string, int> mp;

        if(len*size > n)
            return ans;

        for(auto x:words)
            mp[x]++;

        for(int i = 0; i <= n-(len*size); i++){
            unordered_map<string, int> m;

            for(int j = i; j < i+(len*size); j += len){
                string current = s.substr(j, len);

                if(mp.find(current) == mp.end())
                    break;

                m[current]++;

                if(m[current] > mp[current])
                    break;
            }
            if(mp == m)
                ans.push_back(i);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

