solutions.content:
To understand what will be going on inside my solution, let's discuss some hashing concepts for comparing two sets.

**Concept**
Let's consider we have two unordered sets (it can be multisets too, no problem) as **s1** and **s2**. Now, we need to determine whether these two sets are equal or not. Here, being **equal** means if we sort these two sets, they will eventually turn out to be the same sets.

**Solution:**
Considering both sets are of equal size, the solution is O(|s|) in runtime and O(1) in space complexity. All we need to do is: find hash values for both sets and compare whether they are the same or not! That's it!
Our hashing function will be:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/bonchitoboys/image_1586102364.png)
where,
* initially **h = 1** and OFFSET is any random value greater than 0. 
* n = size of set

Probability of Collision: O(N / MOD) where N is the number of items in one set. This probability can be written as our hash function is nothing but a polynomial of degree N. (from **Schwartz-Zippel lemma**)

**Main Solution:**

Consider each word from **words** as a single integer! Now the problem can be reduced to the following:

*Find the number of sets in **S** those are equal to set **words***

Example:
 s = "barfoothefoobarman",
 words = ["foo","bar"]

 converted words = ["123", "456"] (just assumed their hash values)
 hash of words = ["999999"] (another assumption)

Now, iterate over each 3 length substring from **S**, calculate their hash values with polynomial string hashing, add the same OFFSET previously used, consider this hash value as an integer from the set and calculate the final hash value for the contiguous substring. It's kind of running a sliding window of length **|words| * |words[0]|** and checking whether the contiguous substring forms an equal set as **words**.

So, that's all!

Total runtime complexity: **O(N * number of words)**
Total space complexity: **O(|s|)**

```
#define MAX 10000
#define MOD 1000000007
#define ll long long
#define OFFSET 7

ll h[MAX + 5], po[MAX + 5];

void pre(string &s)
{
    h[0] = s[0];
    po[0] = 1;
    for(int i = 1; i < s.size(); i++)
    {
        h[i] = ((h[i - 1] * 263) + (s[i])) % MOD;
        po[i] = (po[i - 1] * 263) % MOD;
    }
}

ll getHash(int L, int R)
{
    if(!L) return h[R];
    return (h[R] - ((h[L - 1] * po[R - L + 1])%MOD) + MOD) % MOD;
}

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findSubstring(string s, vector<string>& words) {
        if(s.size() == 0 || words.size() == 0) return vector<int>();
        pre(s);
        ll wH = 1;
        for(auto &word : words)
        {
            ll h = 0;
            for(auto &ch : word)
            {
                h = ((h * 263) + ch) % MOD;
            }
            wH = (wH * (h + OFFSET)) % MOD;
        }
        int tot_len = words[0].size();
        tot_len *= words.size();
        int plen = words[0].size();
        vector<int>indices;
        for(int i = 0; i + tot_len <= s.size(); i++)
        {
            ll substr_hash = 1;
            for(int j = i, idx = 0; idx < words.size(); idx++, j += plen)
            {
                int L = j;
                int R = j + plen - 1;
                if(R >= s.size()) break;
                substr_hash = (substr_hash * (getHash(L, R) + OFFSET)) % MOD;
            }
            if(substr_hash == wH) indices.push_back(i);
        }
        return indices;
    }
};
```

