# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Rather than doing a recursive solution, it seemed simpler and more efficient to use a moving window.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Initialize the `right` pointer as the lentgh of all the `words` items lengths.

For each letter in the `s` string, create a substring from `i` to the `right` pointer, and run a RegEx to break up the result string into an array, where each item length is equal to the `words[0]` length. Sort the array, and compare the string values of both arrays. If they match, save the `i` index.

Retun results.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
function findSubstring(s: string, words: string[]): number[] {
    words.sort();
    let right = words.reduce((acc, curr) => acc += curr.length, 0);
    const results = [];
    for (let i = 0 ; right < s.length + 1 ; i++, right++) {
        let subString = s.substring(i, right).match(new RegExp(`.{1,${words[0].length}}`, 'g')).sort();
        if (JSON.stringify(subString) === JSON.stringify(words)) results.push(i)
    };
    return results;
};
```

