I notice that a lot of solutions given by the community is not optimal or even get TLE. So I am contributing my solution here.

# Notation
Let $n$ be length of s, $w$ be length of a word, $m$ be the number of words.

# Observation
- It's obvious that this is a fix-length sliding window problem
- The string of appropriate length ending at $i$th character extends the string ending at the $i-w$th character

# Intuition and Approach
- Maintain a dictionary for each coset (or say index shift) (i.e., $i \to i+w \to i+2w \dots$)
- For each endpoint $i$
	- update the dictionary in $O(w)$, the code speaks for itself
	- check if the condition is satisfied in $O(1)$

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(nw)$
- Space complexity: $O(mw^2)$
If we use rolling string hash, the complexity can be further reduced to Time $O(n)$, space $O(mw)$

# Code
```
// by Maxwill Lin, O(w) time O(mw^2) space, beats 95.76%/74.40%
// can use rolling hash to optimize to O(n) tine O(m) space (and becomes probabilistic algorithm)
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findSubstring(string s, vector<string>& words) {
        int n = s.size(), m = words.size(), w = words[0].size();
        unordered_map<string, int> dict;
        vector<int> ans;
        vector<unordered_map<string, int>> dp(w);
        vector<int> passes(w);
        for(auto &word: words) ++dict[word];
        for(int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            auto& cur = dp[i%w];
            auto& pass = passes[i%w];
            // add new word
            if(i >= w-1) {
                string curS = s.substr(i-w+1, w);
                if(dict.contains(curS)) {
                    if(++cur[curS] == dict[curS]) ++pass;
                }
            }
            // remove old word
            if(i >= (m+1)*w-1) {
                string preS = s.substr(i-(m+1)*w+1, w);
                if(dict.contains(preS)) {
                    if(--cur[preS] == dict[preS]-1) --pass;
                }
            }
            // check if satisfied
            if(pass == dict.size()) ans.emplace_back(i-m*w+1);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

