solutions.content:
**Approach: Sliding Window + Hashmap**
**Steps:**
1. Insert the word counts into a hahsmap.
2. Iterate through every substring `str` in `s` with size `len`.
3. Use `l` and `r` to keep track on the starting and ending index.
4. If  `str` in `hashmap` is greater than 0,  `str` can be used for concatenation. Set `str` to in used by decreasing the count of `str` in hashmap. 
3. If `str` in `hashmap` is 0, the `str` might be already in used. Remove the substring starting from `l` until the `str` is not in used. If still `str` in `hashmap` is 0, `str` is not a string in `words`. Move to next iteration.
5. Add `l` to the result when the window size `r - l` is equals to  `number of word * length of word`. 

**Example:**
If the length of word is 3, we can iterate through every substring in 3 iterations by changing the starting index to `0, 1 and 2`. 

1st iteration:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/612a06de-d098-4c5e-b9a0-5137e3b5d242_1660380232.6132529.png)

2nd iteration:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3cc8e0ce-661a-4e5a-a749-238fa6ceb16c_1660380274.0505571.png)

3rd iteration:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/105ab42a-6c17-462d-b205-09399988f2e8_1660380293.1976612.png)

**Code**

```
vector<int> findSubstring(string s, vector<string>& words) {
    int len = words.front().size();

    vector<int> res;
    for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        unordered_map<string, int> counter;
        for (const string& s: words) counter[s]++;

        for (int l = i, r = i + len; r <= s.size(); r += len) {
            const string& str = s.substr(r - len, len);
            while (counter[str] == 0 && l < r - len) {
                counter[s.substr(l, len)]++;
                l += len;
            }

            if (counter[str] == 0) {
                l += len;
                continue;
            }

            counter[str]--;

            if (r - l == words.size() * len) {
                res.push_back(l);
            }
        }
    }

    return res;
}
