# Approach
We can start by identifying 'O' cells at the border of the board because these cells cannot be surrounded by 'X'. All other 'O' cells within the border can potentially be surrounded and should be marked with  'N'.

# Algorithm
+ Initialize variables to store the number of rows (row) and columns (col) in the matrix.

+ Create a helper function dfs(i, j, mat) that performs Depth-First Search (DFS) to mark 'O' cells and their connected neighbors as 'N'. It should have the following steps:

  + Base case: If the cell (i, j) is out of bounds or already marked as 'N', return.
  + If the cell (i, j) is 'O', mark it as 'N'.
  + Recursively call dfs on its adjacent cells: down (i+1, j), up (i-1, j), right (i, j+1), and left (i, j-1).
+  Iterate through the entire matrix using two nested loops:
   + For each cell (i, j):
       + Check if mat[i][j] is equal to 'O' and if (i, j) is a corner cell (i.e., (i, j) is on the border). You can use the isCorner function for this.
       + If both conditions are met, call dfs(i, j, mat) to mark this region as 'N' and all connected 'O' cells.
+ After marking all potentially surrounded regions as 'N', iterate through the entire matrix again:

   + For each cell (i, j):
       + If mat[i][j] is 'O', change it to 'X' because it is not part of a surrounded region.
       + If mat[i][j] is 'N', change it back to 'O' to restore the originally marked 'O' cells.
+ The matrix is now updated with the correct regions captured. The regions surrounded by 'X' remain 'X', and the regions not surrounded are restored to 'O'.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: **O(row*col)**

- Space complexity:**O(1)**

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int row,col; // Variables to store the number of rows and columns in the matrix.

    // Function to check if a cell is at the corner of the matrix.
    inline bool isCorner(int i,int j){return (i==0 || j==0 || i==row-1 || j==col-1);}

    // Depth-First Search (DFS) function to mark 'O' cells connected to the border as 'N'.
    void dfs(int i,int j,vector<vector<char>>&mat){

        // Base case: If the cell is out of bounds, return.
        if(i<0 || j<0 || i>=row || j>=col) {return;}

        // If the cell is 'O', mark it as 'N' and explore its neighbors.
        if(mat[i][j]=='O') {mat[i][j]='N';}
        else {return;}

        dfs(i+1,j,mat); // Explore down.
        dfs(i-1,j,mat); // Explore up.
        dfs(i,j+1,mat); // Explore right.
        dfs(i,j-1,mat); // Explore left.
    }

    // Main function to solve the problem.
    void solve(vector<vector<char>>& mat) {
        row=mat.size(); // Get the number of rows in the matrix.
        col=mat[0].size(); // Get the number of columns in the matrix.

        // Iterate through the matrix to find 'O' cells at the border and start DFS.
        for(int i=0;i<row;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<col;j++){
                if(mat[i][j]=='O' && isCorner(i,j)){
                    dfs(i,j,mat);
                }
            }
        }

        // Final pass to update 'O' cells to 'X' and 'N' cells back to 'O'.
        for(int i=0;i<row;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<col;j++){
                if(mat[i][j] =='O') mat[i][j]='X';
                else if(mat[i][j] =='N') mat[i][j]='O';
            }
        }
    }
};

