## **Approach:** 
1. First call recursion on the left subtree.
2. Then increment the count by 1 (storing the position of that element when arranged in increasing order)
3. If the count is equal to k, then we return that value. Else we recurse the right subtree.

* If we come across a null node, return -1 so that we can differentiate the node values from null.
* After traversing the left subtree, check whether the returned value is unequal to k. If yes, return the value. Else, traverse the right side.

## **Example**
For a BST: [5,3,6,2,4,null,null,1] and k=4 the traversal would look like the following:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b17130b9-567a-423f-adbb-e7578190848d_1650283426.9845426.png)

## **Code**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int c=0;
    int kthSmallest(TreeNode* root, int k) {
        if(!root)return -1;
        int p=kthSmallest(root->left,k);
        if(p!=-1)return p;
        ++c;
        if(c==k) return root->val;
        return kthSmallest(root->right,k);
    }
};
```
**Time Complexity:** O(n) in worst case as we will traverse all the nodes once.
**Space Complexity:** O(n) due the recursive stack.

